{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22569"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22569"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.41,0.05,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15532"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"912"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"2259"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"41650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a seven-month history of worsening breathlessness associated with a non-productive cough and headache. She has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease diagnosed four years ago. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history and does not take any regular medications. She works as an office administrator.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Her face is swollen with a suffused pink colour. Her voice is hoarse. Ophthalmological examination reveals right-sided ptosis and a constricted pupil. There is temporal wasting and her BMI is 19 kg/m\u00b2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small cell lung cancer","Non-small cell lung cancer","Thyroid carcinoma","Lymphoma","Mesothelioma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of superior vena caval obstruction (facial swelling, suffused pink colour) and Horner\u0027s syndrome (ptosis, miosis), which are characteristic of a Pancoast tumour. These tumours arise in the apex of the lung and compress surrounding structures including the superior vena cava, brachial plexus, and cervical sympathetic chain (Image). The history of significant smoking and constitutional symptoms (weight loss, temporal wasting) strongly suggests an underlying malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;width:100%;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth style=\u0022padding:8px;text-align:left;\u0022\u003EClinical Feature\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth style=\u0022padding:8px;text-align:left;\u0022\u003EAnatomical Structure Involved\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003EFacial swelling and plethora\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003ESuperior vena cava\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003EHorner\u0027s syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003ECervical sympathetic chain\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003EShoulder and arm pain\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003EBrachial plexus (C8-T1 nerve roots)\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003EHoarseness\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003ERecurrent laryngeal nerve\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003EHand weakness and wasting\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding:8px;\u0022\u003ET1 nerve root and ulnar nerve\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-small cell lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for over 95% of Pancoast tumours, with squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma being the most common histological subtypes. The strong smoking history in this patient makes non-small cell lung cancer the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cell lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically arises centrally rather than in the lung apex and is less commonly associated with Pancoast syndrome. While it can cause superior vena caval obstruction, it rarely presents as a Pancoast tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E can invade locally and cause hoarseness through recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement, but it would not typically cause Horner\u0027s syndrome or present as an apical lung mass. Additionally, examination would usually reveal a thyroid mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause superior vena caval obstruction but typically presents with lymphadenopathy, B symptoms (fever, night sweats), and would not usually cause the specific combination of Horner\u0027s syndrome with superior vena caval obstruction seen in Pancoast tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesothelioma\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with asbestos exposure rather than smoking and typically presents as pleural thickening or effusion rather than an apical mass. It would be an extremely rare cause of Pancoast syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Superior vena caval syndrome and Horner\u0027s syndrome are characteristic features of a Pancoast tumour.","Non-small cell lung cancer, particularly squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma, accounts for over 95% of Pancoast tumours.","Smoking history and constitutional symptoms increase suspicion for underlying malignancy in patients with superior vena caval obstruction."],"references":["Panagopoulos N, Leivaditis V, Koletsis E, Prokakis C, Alexopoulos P, Baltayiannis N. Pancoast tumors: characteristics and preoperative assessment. J Thorac Dis. 2014 Mar;6 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S108-15. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2013.12.29. PMID: 24672686; PMCID: PMC3966151. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24672686/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22569"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T17:41:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T17:42:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15532"}},"content":{"dat